               <head>Miscellaneous works, a-c</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>Collection of miscellaneous works containing a) diplomatic letters and petitions; b) 3 stories in prose; c) verses by various poets. IOL stamp 24 Jun 1912. Mica-flecked ink text throughout. Not dated </summary>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85100074 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2005001641" n="1" xml:id="Uk_IO_Islamic_3818-item1">
                     <locus from="2r" to="20v">ff. 2r-20v</locus>
                     <note>
                        <p>Poorly transcribed collection of Safavid and Timurid or Mughal diplomatic letters and petitions largely from the mid to late seventeenth century, mentioning Emperor ʿĀlamgīr, Shāh Sulaymān, Prince Dārā Shukūh, Prince Shāh Shujāʿ, Prince Murād Bakhsh, Sīvājī, Sanbhā son of Sīvājī commenting on Prince Muḥammad Akbar's rebellion </p>
                        <p>Miscellaneous annotations with dated entries (20 Rabīʿ al-Avval 1208/26 October 1793; 1212/1797-98) </p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="per">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85121918" n="2" xml:id="Uk_IO_Islamic_3818-item2">
                     <locus from="21r" to="116r">ff. 21r-116r</locus>
                     <note>
                        <p>Collection of 3 ḥakāyāt or stories in prose: 1) the brick maker and his son; 2) Emperor ʿĀdil Shāh and his son, Malik ʿAlī; 3) Ashraf Khān the just </p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="per">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85100085" n="3" xml:id="Uk_IO_Islamic_3818-item3">
                     <locus from="117r" to="126r"/>
                     <note>
                        <p>Brief collection of poems (ghazal, mas̲navī, and qiṭʿah) ascribed to Khāqānī, Mihrī and Kaws̲arī</p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="per">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
